##  The Communications Planning Flow

### Step 1: Plan Communications Management
**Purpose**: Determine stakeholder information needs and define communication approach
**Key Outputs**:
- Communications Management Plan
- Communication methods and technologies
- Update frequency schedules

### Communication Planning Inputs

| Input | Use |
|:------|:----|
| **Stakeholder Register** | Who needs information |
| **Stakeholder Engagement Plan** | How to engage each |
| **Organizational Process Assets** | Templates, lessons learned |
| **Enterprise Environmental Factors** | Culture, technology, regulations |

---

##  Communications Management Plan

The Communications Management Plan documents:

| Component | Description | Example |
|:----------|:------------|:--------|
| **Stakeholder Information Needs** | What each stakeholder needs | Sponsor: project status, issues, decisions |
| **Information to Communicate** | What content is shared | Status reports, risk updates, milestone reports |
| **Reason for Distribution** | Why this communication | Regulatory requirement, stakeholder request |
| **Timeframe/Frequency** | When/how often | Weekly, daily, on-change |
| **Responsible Party** | Who creates/sends | PM, Team Lead, PMO |
| **Recipients** | Who receives | Sponsor, Steering Committee, Team |
| **Methods/Technologies** | How delivered | Email, meeting, dashboard |
| **Escalation Procedures** | How issues are escalated | Time-based, severity-based |
| **Glossary** | Common terms defined | Avoiding misunderstanding |

